Annual CSU Haunted Takeover

MANKATO, Minn. –The Student Events Team will be putting on their Annual CSU Haunted Takeover. It will be a fearful experience.

This Halloween season the Student Events Team will put fear into you with the theme of, “Scarry TV.” It will entail new routes within the Centennial Student Union with transformation of separate rooms that will be created into Scary TV Shows. This year, there is a new and scarier element to the takeover of the CSU. It’s the first outdoor element, with weather permitting. Be prepared for a night of screams

Enter if you dare the CSU doors located across from the fountain. This is free to students and open to the public for a $5 admission. Make sure to wear closed toe shoes, as well as, no outside food or drink is allowed in the haunted takeover. Dress appropriately for the weather. Arrive early to avoid long lines!

"I am excited to hopefully have the turnout of 1500+ students show up to take part in the festivities. It’s really fun and haunting event that each year gets better and better." –Dustin Slaughter, Student Events Team Special Events.

No cameras or flash photography are prohibited. Age viewers’ discretion is advised.

The Student Events Team is a student-led organization that produces fun, interactive, educational events where students make lifelong memories and celebrate their Maverick pride.

All participants video a custom made scary movie and movie with rules before entering.

In support of our mission, the University of Maryland Division of Student Affairs accepts sponsorships under strict guidelines. The Division of Student Affairs reserves the right to refuse any sponsorship we believe is incompatible with our mission and values. 

Sponsorship Guidelines
		
•	The Division of Student Affairs has sole discretion for determining the types of sponsorships that will be accepted.  The presence of a sponsorship does not imply in any manner endorsement of the sponsor or sponsor’s product. 
 
•	The Division of Student Affairs will not accept a sponsorship that, in our sole opinion, is not in good taste. We will not permit a) a sponsorship involving illegal or objectionable products or services, or b) a sponsorship that is offensive to any individual or group of individuals based on age, color, national origin, race, religion, sex, sexual orientation, or handicap.

•	The sponsorship will not be accepted if it promotes any of the following: alcohol, firearms, ammunition, fireworks, gambling, pornography, tobacco or feminine hygiene products.

•	Sponsored content on our sites, in publications and other collateral materials is clearly labeled as such and the sponsoring organizations are identified.

•	The Division of Student Affairs reserves the right to reject, cancel, or remove any sponsorship at any time. We will provide reasonable notice to the sponsor upon rejection, cancellation, or removal of any sponsorship.

•	No sponsorship shall be permitted that may injure the good name or reputation of the University of Maryland or the Division of Student Affairs.

Sponsor Tabling Guidelines
•	The Division of Student Affairs, Adele H. Stamp Student Union-Center for Campus Life, and Campus Recreation Services has designated space for sponsor tabling. Dates must be approved and scheduled in advance by the appropriate Division of Student Affairs sponsorship liaison. Cancellations can only be honored if they are made 7 days in advance to the appropriate Division of Student Affairs sponsorship liaison. Dates are based on availability and on a first come first serve basis.  Exclusivity is not guaranteed. 

•	During tabling days or events, sponsors may not solicit students, faculty/staff, parents, etc. to sign any binding contracts, account agreements or commitment for a good/service. Sponsors may however allow people to give contact information to use at a later date. The sponsor cannot require this information to be provided in exchange for an item, certificate, entry into a raffle, etc. 

•	Sponsors may not distribute food items during their tabling days. Sponsors may however work with the Division of Student Affairs Department of Dining Services to arrange an on-campus food vendor from the Stamp Food Court to purchase and distribute food from an on-campus food vendor. Packaged food may be considered if it is a Pepsi product or a Pepsi subsidiary product that is pre-packaged and sealed, but must receive prior approval from the Division of Student Affairs Department of Dining Services.  Sampling and/or open food is not allowed at all.

Trap&B Artist Fetty Wap to Perform at Minnesota State Mankato
Tickets Available for Public Purchase
Mankato, Minn. – Trap&B artist Fetty Wap will perform on the Summit and Jacob Heights stage in Minnesota State University, Mankato’s Myers Field House during the University’s Homecoming week. American rapper Silentó will open for Fetty Wap 


Fetty Wap is an American rapper, singer and songwriter whose debut single "Trap Queen" reached number two on the U.S. Billboard Hot 100 chart in May 2015. Other Fetty Wap top 10 hits include “My Way” and “679.”


Among his many awards and nominations, Fetty Wap, won the category of Top New Artist at the 2016 Billboard Music Awards and was named Best New Artist at the 2016 iHeartRadio Music Awards.


Silentó’s debut single, “Watch Me (Whip/Nae Nae),” reached number three on the Hot 100 list, and the song’s YouTube video has reached over 1.5 billion views. Silentó was nominated for Top New Artist at the 2016 Billboard Music Awards.


The concert, presented by Minnesota State Mankato’s Student Events Team and radio station Hot 96.7, is for all ages.


Tickets may be purchased online at www.mnsuevents.com or at Minnesota State Mankato’s Student Activities front desk, located in the Centennial Student Union, Room 173.


Public tickets are $30. A limited number of tickets will be made available to Minnesota State Mankato students for an “early-bird special” price of $5. After those tickets are distributed, Minnesota State Mankato students may purchase tickets for $15 each. Student guest tickets (one per student) are available for $25.


Last year all student tickets sold out in six hours, said Bill Tourville, assistant director of campus programs at Minnesota State Mankato.


Homecoming VIP pre-party tickets are $50 for students and the public. The party package, sponsored by Summit and Jacob Heights and hosted by Hot 96.7, includes free food, beverages, signed merchandise, early access to the best general admission spot and a picture with Silentó.


Doors will open at 6:30 p.m. on concert night, and there is no re-entry to the concert once a patron leaves. Parking will be available in Lot 20. No outside food, beverages, backpacks or flash photography is allowed. Minnesota State Mankato bans weapons on campus and is an alcohol-, drug- and tobacco-free campus. Use of substances will result in removal from the concert.


A special reception with free tickets to the concert is available to alumni of the Student Events Team, IMPACT and University Programs. For more information on the special reception or concert, contact Bill Tourville by email at william.tourville@mnsu.edu or by phone at 507-389-6076.


Minnesota State Mankato’s Student Events team is a student-led organization that produces fun, interactive and educational events for students to create lifelong memories and celebrate their Maverick pride. The Student Events Team meets every Tuesday at 4 p.m. in Centennial Student Union 245, and students interested in joining or volunteering with the group are welcome to attend the meetings.


Minnesota State Mankato, a comprehensive university with 14,712 students, is part of the Minnesota State system, which includes 30 colleges and seven universities.

data.description: Earth Fair is an annual event hosted by Associated Student Productions that celebrates Earth Day. The ultimate goal of Earth Fair is to educate students in interactive and innovative ways about how to sustain and care for our planet Earth. Each year the theme is changed to capture attention and focus the event on the prominent environmental issues facing our society. The largest component of Earth Fair is the 50 to 60 on-campus, local, and outside vendors that are relevant to the Earth Fair theme and impact student learning. Local and outside vendors show students that goods and services that consumers buy everyday can be bought from companies that have less of a carbon footprint. CSUN departments and auxiliaries provide students the opportunity to learn about the sustainable developments the campus has implemented in day to day activities.

data.description: Relay for Life is a 12 hour event held at schools across the country to raise money for the American Cancer Society. Adelphi holds the event every year and students, faculty, and community members come together to raise money and support the fight against cancer. Everyone is encouraged to walk the indoor track with the idea being that cancer never sleeps so for one night, neither do we. We also sell raffles and sponsors as well as student organizations hold fundraising tables in the gym selling things such as cupcakes or coffee to raise additional money. Attendees are kept entertained throughout the night with performances from student groups such as the various dance groups, song performed in American Sign Language, and strolls from our multi-cultural greek organizations. In addition, there are inflatables, games, and contests such as musical chairs and egg tosses that are played throughout the night. The event takes on special meaning with the luminaria ceremony to remember our loved ones lost to cancer and the opening and closing ceremonies reminding people why we are there and to motivate them to join the fight against cancer!

data.description: UDance, the largest student-run philanthropy at the University of Delaware, is a year long effort to raise funds and awareness for the fight against pediatric cancer, while instilling hope in children suffering from these diseases. Our efforts culminate in a 12-hour dance marathon every March which is attended by over 6,000 members of the UD community. UDance partners with The Andrew McDonough B+ Foundation to provide direct and immediate financial aid to families affected by childhood cancer while also funding cutting-edge research. Since its inception in 2007, UDance has raised over $9 million, and in 2018, the UD community raised over $2 million. Furthermore, UDance offers emotional support to these children, the B+ Heroes, by pairing them with various organizations at UD. Our B+ Heroes attend UDance every year where they are treated as celebrities by their organizations, and are able to participate in Hero Hour where we hold a special talent show. Throughout the day of UDance, we have a variety of performers from student dance teams, to local bands, to Zumba instructors. Last year, we had the viral Cardinal  Shehan School Choir perform, as well as child star Angelina Green from America's Got Talent.

data.description: UADM exists to provide financial and emotional assistance to the children and families undergoing treatment or who have been previously treated at the Children’s Miracle Network Hospital, Children’s of Alabama, in Birmingham, AL. UADM is entirely student-run and is proud to have become a tradition on campus and in the community. The Main Event, the flagship event of UADM, is a nationwide movement, involving college and high school students at over 150 schools across the nation who raise money for the Children’s Miracle Network hospital in their community. UADM is a year-long initiative that concludes with a 13.1-hour event, the Main Event, where over 1,200 students play games, dance, and stand in solidarity with the children treated at Children’s of Alabama and their families. Each hour of the event is themed, and students participate in fundraising pushes and competitions to match the theme. Past themes have included Tacky Tourist Hour, Fourth Quarter Hour and Carnival Hour. The event concludes with a rave hour, followed by the Circle of Hope and a performance by No Strings Attached - an a capella student group at UA, and our final total reveal in which we celebrate the year's fundraising efforts. Why stay on your feet for that long? To quote the first Children’s Miracle Network Dance Marathon’s mission statement: “We dance for those who can’t.” It is this solidarity and connection with the cause that makes the UADM Main Event an event unlike any other.

data.description:
The High School Leadership Conference (HSLC) is a three day adventure into leadership for high school juniors from across the nation. HSLC is an event that is hosted annually at the University of Oklahoma and has existed for 21 years. The goal of this conference is to equip, empower, and inspire high school students with valuable leadership skills that will enable them to create an impact in their schools and communities. HSLC campers are primarily students who are seeking opportunities to learn more about their leadership style and develop as a leader. Additionally, HSLC campers are often first-generation Americans and students seeking higher education and more personal development as they move forward in life. Students will leave HSLC with characteristics that help them become more caring, capable, and efficient leaders for the rest of their lives.


HSLC is planned and programmed entirely by an executive committee of 100 OU students. These students apply and are selected out of hundreds of applicants each year.  Additionally, the executive committee is led by a selected Chair, Executive Vice Chair, and respective Vice Chairs overseeing Programming, Operations, Counselors, Publicity, Recruitment, and Creative committees. The Executive Committee works from September to February to recruit prospective students, program the events of the weekend, acquire sponsorship, design creative elements, facilitate leadership development, and publicize the conference. In addition to the 300 high school juniors who are expected to attend the conference, the Executive Committee is involved in the three day event as well.


HSLC 2018, which took place between February 16-18, 2018 hosted 297 high school juniors from across the state of Oklahoma and states such as Texas, Indiana, Arkansas, and Missouri.  Over 500 students from 155 different high schools schools applied to come to the conference, of which 300 students were accepted and 297 were able to attend. Through fundraising and generous sponsors, HSLC awarded $8,100 in tuition waivers, including full tuition waivers for 31 attendees (normal cost of attendance is $135). The majority of HSLC's fundraising and sponsorship resources are used to fulfill tuition waivers to ensure that all campers can attend the conference.


Upon surveying the attendees, 97.6% of the respondents indicated that they had learned something about a perspective or culture other than their own. Additionally, 98.8% said that they left the conference feeling equipped, empowered, and inspired, the three pillars of HSLC's mission. Finally, 79.3% of respondents indicated that they were then considering OU for their collegiate experience, and 50.6% were interested in concurrent enrollment at OU. HSLC is an incredibly effective event in guiding students and developing them for the future.

data.description: Midnight Breakfast is a biannual event that the Georgia Institute of Technology hosts at the end of every semester in the Student Center for our students and faculty. We serve breakfast from 7:00 - 12:00 pm on a night during finals week to give students a chance to take a break from their studying and destress a little bit as well as give them some comfort food to help them get through with their studying when they return to it. We have professors of the school serve the food, which adds a little extra lightness to the stress of finals. Along with the breakfast, we have a number of relaxation activities, including massages, crafts, and spending time with therapy dogs. The event is completely free and doesn’t require a ticket or an RSVP, but to better handle the long lines that form, people can sign up to come during a specific time slot to get into a shorter, fast-track line.

data.description: Frost Fest is one of the biggest events of the year hosted by the SAPB at Binghamton. Our goal is to help cultivate our community’s vibrance by peaking students’ and residents’ interest in a sense of community and by fostering relationships through attendance at the Frost Fest Festival. The festival has a near decade history of success in spreading winter cheer with food, fun, and community. Thanks to the participation of over 2,000 students, community members and their families, Frost Fest also serves as the center for a Canned Food Drive for a local Binghamton food pantry. The event is tabled by many of the over 300+ clubs and student organizations at Binghamton and local businesses as well. There are also featured performances from student  groups such as Binghamton Hoop Troop, No Strings Attached, Chanbara, Liberty Belle and the Union Boys, Bing Stand Up, ProjectDCX, Explorchestra, Cabbage, Harpur Vocal Jazz, Collection Romantic Autumn and The Setbacks. The groups compete for the best-decorated table, highlight their presence on campus, and display their organizational activities. In years past, the festival has featured an Escape Room, a glow in the dark Arcade Room , and other thematic activities. Attendees may enjoy thematic food and our partnership with local food places such as Lupo's S&S Char Pit and Moghul's Fine Indian Cuisine, which have become classic participants at Frost Fest. Overall a fun community event for all who attend!

data.description: Each year, the University of Cincinnati Dance Marathon hosts an event called BearcatThon, 12-hour fundraiser, celebration, and event that raises money and awareness for Cincinnati Children's Hospital. It is a year-long fundraising and planning effort in conjunction with Children's Miracle Network Hospitals that aid youth patients who are being cared for at Cincinnati Children's Hospital. During BearcatThon, students, corporate sponsors, faculty, patients and their families, and community sponsors will come together for this 12-hour event. There are various in-event activities such as a silent disco room, inflatable obstacle course, face-painting, cornhole, game room and more. Furthermore, there are tons of in-event fundraisers that raise money for the Hospital such as Pie-an-Exec, raffle tickets, fundraising challenges. In support of our mission, the University of Maryland Division of Student Affairs accepts sponsorships under strict guidelines. The Division of Student Affairs reserves the right to refuse any sponsorship we believe is incompatible with our mission and values. 

Sponsorship Guidelines
		
•	The Division of Student Affairs has sole discretion for determining the types of sponsorships that will be accepted.  The presence of a sponsorship does not imply in any manner endorsement of the sponsor or sponsor’s product. 
 
•	The Division of Student Affairs will not accept a sponsorship that, in our sole opinion, is not in good taste. We will not permit a) a sponsorship involving illegal or objectionable products or services, or b) a sponsorship that is offensive to any individual or group of individuals based on age, color, national origin, race, religion, sex, sexual orientation, or handicap.

•	The sponsorship will not be accepted if it promotes any of the following: alcohol, firearms, ammunition, fireworks, gambling, pornography, tobacco or feminine hygiene products.

•	Sponsored content on our sites, in publications and other collateral materials is clearly labeled as such and the sponsoring organizations are identified.

•	The Division of Student Affairs reserves the right to reject, cancel, or remove any sponsorship at any time. We will provide reasonable notice to the sponsor upon rejection, cancellation, or removal of any sponsorship.

•	No sponsorship shall be permitted that may injure the good name or reputation of the University of Maryland or the Division of Student Affairs.

Sponsor Tabling Guidelines
•	The Division of Student Affairs, Adele H. Stamp Student Union-Center for Campus Life, and Campus Recreation Services has designated space for sponsor tabling. Dates must be approved and scheduled in advance by the appropriate Division of Student Affairs sponsorship liaison. Cancellations can only be honored if they are made 7 days in advance to the appropriate Division of Student Affairs sponsorship liaison. Dates are based on availability and on a first come first serve basis.  Exclusivity is not guaranteed. 

•	During tabling days or events, sponsors may not solicit students, faculty/staff, parents, etc. to sign any binding contracts, account agreements or commitment for a good/service. Sponsors may however allow people to give contact information to use at a later date. The sponsor cannot require this information to be provided in exchange for an item, certificate, entry into a raffle, etc. 

•	Sponsors may not distribute food items during their tabling days. Sponsors may however work with the Division of Student Affairs Department of Dining Services to arrange an on-campus food vendor from the Stamp Food Court to purchase and distribute food from an on-campus food vendor. Packaged food may be considered if it is a Pepsi product or a Pepsi subsidiary product that is pre-packaged and sealed, but must receive prior approval from the Division of Student Affairs Department of Dining Services. data.description:
Something very special has a habit of sweeping into Norman, Oklahoma during the final weekend of October each year. A spirit of unity, legacy, celebration, and pride ignites the very atmosphere that surrounds the tradition that is Homecoming Reunion Week at the University of Oklahoma, marking an experience fully dedicated to creating opportunities for the entire Sooner Family to celebrate the power of old memories as well as the chance to forge new ones. From time-honored events like the Rah! Rally and the Parade to innovative new experiences like the Homecoming Bash Concert, our events honor both the pages of history that hold memories and traditions special to so many as well the sense of possibility that drives the University forward into exciting new chapters. We are so grateful to attend a university that values student input and creativity, and are humbled to be trusted with the opportunity to play a part in planning such an incredible reunion week for the thousands of people who experience Homecoming each year.


Homecoming Reunion Week is one of the oldest and largest events that takes place at the University of Oklahoma, uniting all members of the Sooner Family. Homecoming provides a vital function to the University in the unique way that it is able to touch so many facets of the Sooner Family at once, whether through drawing in prospective students, retaining current ones, or prompting the return of special alumni to campus. We pride ourselves on creating a week of events that properly reflects the high caliber and dynamic nature of the students and alumni that Homecoming is designed for. Comprehensibly, these high caliber events come at a high cost. Last year we were allotted $10,000 to plan the week’s worth of events. In the end, the costs associated with Homecoming totaled over $50,000. The Homecoming Executive Committee works diligently to ensure these funds are spent responsibly and in a way that maximizes impact on as many people as possible. It is also a priority of our committee to plan an inclusive Homecoming. With your office’s support last year, we were able to reach a broader audience than ever through implementing new traditions as well as sustaining overall growth.


As we plan for Homecoming, we have conducted open feedback meetings and student surveys to ensure that our event reflects the needs and desires of those it aims to serve. We have also worked hard to continue our relationship with the 15+ departmental stakeholders that play a role in contributing to the success of Homecoming, such as the Athletic Department, the Alumni Association, and OU Fire/OUPD.  In regards to the student experience, this year we have worked harder than ever before to restructure the competitive aspect of Homecoming so that as many student organizations as possible can participate in a manner that will best create fond memories of OU for their members. To accomplish this, we conducted individual outreach meetings with the leaders of over 50 different student organizations ranging from all five Greek systems, to multicultural groups, to academic societies. In response to feedback we received, Homecoming has created additional channels through which organizations can participate ranging from individual options, to self-selected pairings, to random pairings that introduce student collaboration that may not have otherwise have had the opportunity to occur. To best support the participating organizations, the Homecoming Executive Committee has assigned a faculty/staff Group Guide as well as a student Development Coordinator to each pairing. These individuals volunteer to be objective resources to help facilitate positive conversations regarding group equity, planning, and healthy conflict resolution among groups. As a result of these changes, 48 different student organizations will be competing in this year’s Homecoming compared to the 41 that competed in .


In addition to this increased emphasis on the relationships that Homecoming can build and the memories that it can create, we are also expanding events to be more accessible to different demographics of the student body who might not identify with a particular student organization. With the now two-year success of Homecoming’s first ever entirely non-competitive event, the Homecoming Bash Concert, we look forward to building off of the momentum we have created and refining the event to reach more students than ever with possibilities like holding the concert in the heart of OU’s campus: the South Oval. Building on this initiative of creating non-competitive opportunities for student engagement, Homecoming will be debuting a brand new event this year with our first annual Trivia Night. As we progress through the planning stages, we are excited to introduce an event that reaches a different dimension of the student body as well as promotes an environment where competing organizations and noncompeting students can come together in one room to create lasting memories.


Passion and innovation are hallmarks of the 35 students who make up the Homecoming Executive Committee, and we desire to build on the incredible progress of Homecoming . Last year saw innovations such as an expanded Philanthropy event, the reprise of the non-competitive Homecoming Bash Concert, and an elevated commitment to making events inclusive and accessible. We desire to capitalize on this momentum and create as many opportunities as possible for students and alumni alike to experience competitive and non-competitive events that cultivate such intangible opportunities for growth. However, we are struggling to cover costs that will allow us to take action and reach our ultimate goal: creating an environment in which every Sooner feels the sense of belonging, pride, and community that are so central to the identity of the University of Oklahoma.


Inclusive events like these cannot be put on without help. Due to the funds we work with, opportunities for Homecoming Reunion Week 2018 are limited. We plan to continue to make OU Homecoming more inclusive and dynamic than ever through the use of the funds we are requesting, and above all aim to unite students and alumni through designing a Homecoming that is accessible to all.


It is with the deepest sincerity we thank you for your consideration in aiding Homecoming Reunion Week 2018. Homecoming is an event that is like no other in that it brings together the Sooner Family to celebrate one thing we all have in common: our love for the University of Oklahoma. Homecoming is an event that combines tradition and innovation in an unparalleled way, and creates memories that last a lifetime. We thank you for your consideration in helping us progress this event into being the most dynamic, inclusive, and accessible Homecoming Reunion Week yet.
